docs.abstract: Cody Wilson, a Texas champion of gun rights and anarchists, had said he would post blueprints for 3-D printed plastic guns on Wednesday.
docs.snippet: Cody Wilson, a Texas champion of gun rights and anarchists, had said he would post blueprints for 3-D printed plastic guns on Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For years, Cody Wilson, a champion of gun-rights and anarchism from Texas, has waged a battle to post on the internet the blueprints for making plastic guns on 3-D printers, claiming the First Amendment gives him the right to do it.

headline.main: Judge Blocks Attempt to Post Blueprints for 3-D Guns
headline.print_headline: Judge Presses Pause on the Downloadable Gun

byline.original: By Michael D. Shear, Tiffany Hsu and Kirk Johnson

docs.abstract: Ohio State University announced Friday that more than 100 of its former students have come forward to accuse a former team doctor of sexual misconduct.
docs.snippet: Ohio State University announced Friday that more than 100 of its former students have come forward to accuse a former team doctor of sexual misconduct.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — More than 100 former Ohio State University students have come forward with allegations that a team doctor and professor at the school committed some form of sexual misconduct with them, university officials announced Friday, as the university begins to grapple with the sheer scope of a scandal that continues to grow.

headline.main: More Than 100 Former Ohio State Students Allege Sexual Misconduct
headline.print_headline: List of Accusers Grows In Ohio State Scandal

docs.abstract: In a bid to make Washington’s halls of power more diverse, the Senate is seeking to create a $5 million fund to compensate its interns, the first such organized congressional effort in two decades.
docs.snippet: In a bid to make Washington’s halls of power more diverse, the Senate is seeking to create a $5 million fund to compensate its interns, the first such organized congressional effort in two decades.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In the past two years, DaQuawn Bruce received news — not once, but twice — that he had dreamed of since middle school. He had been accepted into two competitive internship programs on Capitol Hill, opportunities that swarms of students vie for every year.

headline.main: Fighting Privilege: The Senate Finally Wants to Pay Its Interns
headline.print_headline: Hill Intern: Exc Oppty w/Access & Perks (No $)

docs.abstract: Pressured by a strong demand for goods, an industry known for older white men is trying to recruit women, teenagers and people of color.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — America’s booming economy has a problem: a shortage of truck drivers.

headline.main: ‘What Does a Trucker Look Like?’ It’s Changing, Amid a Big Shortage

docs.abstract: In addition to ex-wrestlers and coaches, the top three House Republicans have backed Mr. Jordan, a powerful House member who denies he ignored sexual abuse allegations.
docs.snippet: In addition to ex-wrestlers and coaches, the top three House Republicans have backed Mr. Jordan, a powerful House member who denies he ignored sexual abuse allegations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — House Republican leaders and a platoon of former wrestlers have come out in support of Representative Jim Jordan as he deflects allegations that he turned a blind eye to sexual abuse as a wrestling coach at Ohio State, an extraordinary show of solidarity that indicates just how much power the conservative stalwart still wields.

headline.main: Unshaken by Abuse Scandal, Conservatives Are Sticking With Jim Jordan
headline.print_headline: Dogged Defense Emerges For Conservative Stalwart

docs.abstract: Thousands of fans lined the city’s streets to celebrate the Capitals’ Stanley Cup victory, which gave the team its first championship and the city its first major sports title in 26 years.
docs.snippet: Thousands of fans lined the city’s streets to celebrate the Capitals’ Stanley Cup victory, which gave the team its first championship and the city its first major sports title in 26 years.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The word emblazoned across the chests of thousands of Washington Capitals fans had eluded them for over 40 years. But on Tuesday, it was worn with pride: champions.

headline.main: For Washington Capitals Fans, a Celebration Worth the Wait
headline.print_headline: A Capital Celebration: ‘We’ve Been Waiting for Too Long’

docs.snippet: The release offered a rare glimpse of national security wiretap files and raised echoes of a fight in February over the Russia inquiry between Republicans and Democrats on the House Intelligence Committee.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration disclosed on Saturday a previously top-secret set of documents related to the wiretapping of Carter Page, the onetime Trump campaign adviser who was at the center of highly contentious accusations by Republicans on the House Intelligence Committee that the F.B.I. had abused its surveillance powers.

docs.abstract: Senegal deported two former Guantánamo detainees to Libya, raising fears of a broader collapse of Obama-era resettlement deals under President Trump.
docs.snippet: Senegal deported two former Guantánamo detainees to Libya, raising fears of a broader collapse of Obama-era resettlement deals under President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In President Barack Obama’s drive to close the Guantánamo prison, his administration struck deals with about three dozen nations to take in lower-risk detainees from dangerous countries. Resettling them in stable places would increase the chances they would live peacefully, officials argued, rather than face persecution or drift into Islamist militancy.

headline.main: Deported to Libya, Ex-Gitmo Detainees Vanish. Will Others Meet a Similar Fate?
headline.print_headline: Program to Resettle Guantánamo Detainees Shows Signs of Strain

byline.original: By Charlie Savage, Declan Walsh and Dionne Searcey
